text.section:
Subject to the hearing provisions of § 16-602 of this title, the Commission may deny a home inspector license to any applicant, reprimand any home inspector licensee, or suspend or revoke a home inspector license if the applicant or licensee:
fraudulently or deceptively obtains or attempts to obtain a license for the applicant or licensee or for another;
fraudulently or deceptively uses a license;
engages in conduct that demonstrates bad faith, incompetency, negligence or untrustworthiness, or that constitutes dishonest, fraudulent, or improper dealings;
under the laws of the United States or of any state, is convicted of:
a felony; or
a misdemeanor that is directly related to the fitness and qualification of the applicant or licensee to provide home inspection services;
fails to maintain the insurance required under § 16-4A-04 of this title;
violates any provision of this title;
violates any regulation adopted under this title; or
aids, abets, or assists any person in violating any provision of this title or any regulation adopted under this title.

section.section:
To determine the amount of the penalty imposed, the Commission shall consider:
the seriousness of the violation;
the harm caused by the violation;
the good faith of the licensee; and
any history of previous violations by the licensee.

text.section:
The Commission shall consider the following facts in the granting, denial, renewal, suspension, or revocation of a license or the reprimand of a licensee when an applicant or licensee is convicted of a felony or a misdemeanor described in subsection (a)(4) of this section:
the nature of the crime;
the relationship of the crime to the activities authorized by the license;
with respect to a felony, the relevance of the conviction to the fitness and qualification of the applicant or licensee to provide home inspection services;
the length of time since the conviction; and
the behavior and activities of the applicant or licensee before and after the conviction.
